<br>
Actually, the dictionary does not define what a word means, or even how it is spelled.  The purpose of a dictionary is to list the most common spellings and definitions <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>that are in use</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and even that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>were</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in use.<br>
<br>
At least, since 1953 or so.<br>
<br>
&quot;A Table Alphabeticall&quot; is commonly believed to be the first dictionary, written by one man, Robert Cawdry, in 1604.  Lexicographers since then have taken varying stances on the authority of a dictionary, at first being quite militant about it, and gradually coming to the conlusion that people were going to change the language by using it, and they could not realistically make arbitrary desicions as to what was &quot;good&quot; usage and what was &quot;bad&quot; usage.  <br>
<br>
The editors of the 1953 &quot;Webster's First College Edition&quot; stated their position - and opinion - in their forward.  It &quot;was not to create the impression that it was authoritarian, laying down the law; it was to play, rather, the role of a friendly guide, pointing out the safe and well-traveled roads.&quot;<br>
<br>
So although many readers and users of a dictionary believe a dictionary to be the last word on the subject of a definition, or even a spelling, all a dictionary really is, is a collection of the spellings and definitions of a word that are already in use.  The job of the lexicographers is write them down and stick them in a book.  The job of the book is to let us see how other people use the words we toss around so casually.<br>
<br>
So technically, a word is spelled however we fell like spelling it.  And it is defined however we feel like defining it.  Especially if it is done by a significant portion of people, but not necessarily.<br>
<br>
However, I'm not certain that I would recommend arguing this with one's spelling/reading instructor if one happens to have &quot;misspelled&quot; a word on a test and gotten marks off for it.  It is more than likely that one will be sent to the Principal/Administrator's office. Trust me.<br>
<br>
Hildie <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=738724&amp;resize=true" target="top">My Magelo Profile</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
